# Git Workflow

Follow Git Flow-style branching. See also `.claude/CLAUDE.md` for the Claude Code equivalent.

## Branch naming

| Prefix | Use |
|--------|-----|
| `feature/` | New functionality (default) |
| `fix/` | Bug fixes |
| `chore/` | Tooling, deps, config |

Examples: `feature/income-tracking`, `fix/overview-crash`, `chore/update-deps`

## Auto-create branches

When starting **new feature work**, **bug fixes**, or **chore tasks**:

1. Check the current branch (`git branch --show-current`).
2. If on `master` (default branch), automatically create and switch to an appropriately prefixed branch before writing code:
   - New functionality → `feature/<short-kebab-description>`
   - Bug fix → `fix/<short-kebab-description>`
   - Tooling/config → `chore/<short-kebab-description>`
3. Never commit directly to `master`.

## Auto-create commits

Create commits automatically as work completes — do not wait for the user to ask.

**Commit discipline:**

- One logical change per commit; keep commits focused and reviewable.
- Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/): `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`.
- Write professional messages: imperative mood, concise subject (≤ 72 chars), optional body explaining *why* when non-obvious.
- Stage only files relevant to that change — never bundle unrelated work.
- Never commit `.env.local`, credentials, or secrets.

**Examples:**

```
feat: add income pie chart and salary categories

Income transactions were invisible on the dashboard. Adds income
breakdown aggregation, dedicated categories, and a second pie chart.
```

```
fix: guard optional chaining on overview topCategories
```

## Merge gate (user confirmation required)

- **Never** merge into `master`, push to `master`, or open a merge PR unless the user explicitly requests it.
- **Never** force-push to `master`.
- **Never** skip hooks (`--no-verify`) unless the user explicitly asks.

## Merge reminder

When a feature is complete, or at the end of a session with unmerged work on a feature branch, remind the user:

> Work is on `feature/...`. Say when you want me to merge into `master`.
